Region: North America
Industry: Healthcare (Remote-first clinic)
Author: Ssambra — Identity Auditor & Threat Sentinel

1. Executive Summary
A remote-first healthcare clinic experienced repeated failures in its quarterly access review process, resulting in two terminated employees retaining access to ePHI systems for 47 and 63 days respectively.

This report maps the incident to NIST CSF 2.0 (Govern Function) and HIPAA Security Rule requirements, demonstrating how governance failures cascade into operational risk.

The purpose of this crosswalk is to show how a governance-level control (NIST GV) directly impacts HIPAA compliance, evidence collection, and patient privacy.

2. Background
The clinic uses a cloud-based EHR platform and relies on a distributed workforce. Access reviews are conducted manually by department managers using spreadsheets.

During a routine internal audit, discrepancies were found between the HR termination list and the EHR active user list.

